[Until one knows with some certainty how these got infected, it is
scary but how meaningful? How many of these 42 cats are/were farm
cats? How many were suburban cats normally only getting pasteurised
milk? ... did they get it from cheese? Rodents? How many were
enthusiastic hunters? Couch potatoes/window bird-watchers?

From past experience, how do feline cases relate to human
cases/reactors in the same household? Put another way, for every
sentinel cat case, how many human cases might we expect? I say this as
someone who is skin test positive to M.bTB as a result of childhood
exposure to unpasteurised milk, but with no symptoms at any time. On
the other hand my godfather, Ted Robinson, had a spinal M.bTB
infection and as a result lost his toes. - Mod.MHJ]
